Unlike in the past, this will be the only rally action of the day before the cars head to the Kenya Wildlife Service Training Institute in Naivasha, 90 kilometres west of Nairobi, which will be home for the Safari for the following three days.
More Kenyans will also follow the Safari on television in a WRC Promoter high-end production in real time in some sections.  
Proper action resumes on Friday in the expansive Soysambu Conservancy. Cars will enter the rally route on the left at Kikopey Shopping Centre, two kilometres from Gilgil town renowned for mouth-watering Nyama Choma offerings.
Route designers — Gurvi Bhabra, Nazir Yakub, George Mwangi and Anwar Sidi  — have identified several spectator zones at Soysambu and Elmentaita in the east and an open field near Kenya Pipeline Depot overlooking Lion Hills, 10 kilometres westward from Nakuru town.



