The rally team has produced media safety guides highlighting areas with the best action shots for every competitive section, complete with elevations and mobile telephones signals strength.
Indiscipline, like what was seen in Australia in 2018 where a fan was taking pictures close to the road, will not be entertained. These media section will be manned by safety marshals and anybody who crosses the official lines will be reported to the police.
The FIA considers a media accreditation card as a working tool and any abuse of this document can easily jeopardise one’s future applications.
From Gilgil, the cars will return to the KWS Training Institute where fans will easily mingle with the drivers.
The park is taking shape with tarmac surfaces in place and enough room for the Safari Village where fans will follow action in the field from giant TV monitors throughout the duration of the Safari.
Over 64, 40-foot containers will be housed at the Park expected to attract very important personalities from car manufacturers, diplomats to business magnates.
A special mixed zone for mandatory media interviews has been created while the WRC Safari team has identified the KWS land opposite the institute, as the parking area for the fans.



